e scope to which these two legal traditions converge. One of the principal findings of this book is that Shari’ah and common law have many more commonalities than differences. As a result, the need for harmonisation between the two might have been exaggerated. The similarities do not need to be harmonised. Rather, they need to be acknowledged and appreciated. If the differences between Shari’ah and common law, which undoubtedly exist as evidenced in this book, are approached from the position of appreciation for commonalities, the ambiance to reconcile the differences would be more conducive to the harmonisation process which would, in that case, be reflective of compromise. This book is intended to help readers better understand Shari’ah and common law and aid harmonization efforts when needed.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xLaw and legislation. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspects. 0aCommercial law. 0aHuman rights. 4aCOVID-19. 4aGlobale Pandemie. 4aMenschenrechte. 4aRechtliche Implikationen. 4aRechtsstaatlichkeit. 4aWirtschaftsrecht. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Business Law.2bisacsh  aShari’ah and Common Law, Harmonisation of Law, Comparative Law, Law in Asia, Law and Society.1 aAli Mohamed, Ashgar Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGan, Joo-Ee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarim, Ridoan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrishnan, Loganathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLatha Ramalingam, Chithra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMajid, Abdul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMydin Meera, Vazeer Alam, econtributor.4ctb4https